## Recommended: Use `System.IO.Abstractions`

For `File.WriteAllText`, `File.ReadAllText`, and `Directory.Exists`, the best approach is the established **System.IO.Abstractions** NuGet package — no need to write custom wrappers.

### 1. Install packages

```bash
dotnet add <YourProject> package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes

```csharp
public class MyService(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool EnsureDirectory(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});
mockFs.AddDirectory("/data");

var service = new MyService(mockFs);

Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", service.Load("/data/config.json"));
Assert.True(service.EnsureDirectory("/data"));
```

### Why this over a custom wrapper?

| Concern | `System.IO.Abstractions` | Custom `IFileService` |
|---------|--------------------------|----------------------|
| Coverage | All of `File`, `Directory`, `Path`, `Stream` | Only what you wrap |
| Maintenance | Community-maintained | You maintain it |
| Test helpers | `MockFileSystem` included | You build your own |
| Adoption cost | One NuGet install | Write + test wrapper code |

---

Once you've added the package and updated your classes, you can use the **migrate-static-to-wrapper** skill to bulk-replace all `File.*` / `Directory.*` call sites mechanically. Just say the word if you'd like help with that step.
